        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to observe the thermal continuum emission of the disk around
OTS44 at 233 GHz (1.287 mm). OTS 44 is the least massive known object that
hosts a substantial disk, which has been confirmed at 70 micrometer by Herschel.
Through the low sensitivity of pre-ALMA instruments, no measurement
exists in the (sub)mm range. From the modelling of the disk presented in
Joergens et al. (2013) in the worst case (i.e. interstellar-medium grain sizes 
of 0.25 micrometer) the continuum flux in ALMA band 6 at 233 GHz is estimated 
to be 0.0344 mJy. In the more realistic case of at least slight grain growth 
(2.5 micrometer grains), the expected flux is 0.0688 mJy.

Because of the faintness of the source,
our strategy is to maximize the sensitivity of the array by proposing a
spatially unresolved observation with the most compact array
configuration. The object will be detected as point source, therefore a
discussion of the field-of-view, the resolvable scale and mosaic-imaging
can be neglected and the integrated continuum flux represents already the
faintest peak continuum flux. All four spectral windows shall operate in
the TDM mode with dual polarization. Spectral line observations are
excluded to minimize the on-source time. Finally, the considered bandwidth
is 7.5 GHz with a spectral resolution of 31.25 MHz.

To achieve a signal to noise ratio of at least 3 in the worst case 
scenario (0.25 micrometer grain sizes), the necessary
sensitivity is 0.011 mJy, corresponding to an on-source time of 2.44 h.
In the more realistic case of at least slight grain growth (2.5 micrometer
grains), we will achieve a SNR of 6 with these observations. 
Including all overheads and calibrator source observations the required
total time for this science goal is ~4.5 h.

Besides the estimation of the observing time with the ALMA sensitivity
calculator, we simulated a synthetic ALMA observation with CASA 4.2 (Fig. 3). This
simulation includes the influence of thermal and phase noise through of
the water vapour in the atmosphere by PWV = (1.262 +- 0.15) mm. It shows
the feasibility of the proposed observation and a sufficient u-v coverage.

With 2.2 MB/s the data rate is acceptable low.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
