    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>OTS44 is one of only two free-floating planets known to have a disk. We have recently shown that it is the coolest and least massive known free-floating planet (~12 Jupitermasses) with a substantial Herschel-detected disk that is actively accreting. We propose to observe the thermal continuum emission of this faint source with ALMA in two bands (0.74 and 1.3 mm) with the goal 
to investigate if mm-sized dust grains are present in the disk and to accurately determine the disk dust mass (not possible with Herschel). This will be the first mm-observations and characterization of a disk around a free-floating planet and push ALMA to its current limits. They will allow us to study disk physics in an extremely low-gravity and -temperature environment and to crucially constrain models for dust evolution in proto-planetary disks. We will address the question if grain growth, as the first step of planet formation, can occur in a disk around a free-floating planet. This would show that the process that forms planetary systems like our own works all the way down to small-mass planets orbiting Super-Jupiters. That would be key information for star and planet formation theories.</prp:abstract>
